## `<file-level: overview>`
<!-- checksum: rust-fdtable-1 -->

### Purpose
In-memory table of open file descriptors for one `Filesystem`. Each fd maps to an `FdEntry` with the inode, open flags, and captured `(uid, gid)` at open time. Required for:
- permission enforcement on read/write (the access mode captured at open, not on every op),
- lock ownership (OFD and flock are fd-scoped),
- inode GC (the `Filesystem` defers `nodes::delete` while any fd references the inode).

Module owns no SQLite state — pure in-memory struct.

### Implementation Notes

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;

use crate::errors::{Error, Result};
```

---

## `pub struct FdEntry`
<!-- checksum: rust-fdtable-2 -->

### Purpose
One row per open fd.

### Postconditions
- `fd: u64`         — library-level fd number.
- `inode: u64`      — target node.
- `flags: i32`      — the `O_*` flags passed to `open()`.
- `uid: u32, gid: u32` — identity captured at open time.
- `offset: u64`     — reserved for a future default-offset read/write API; always 0 in v1.

### Implementation Notes

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub struct FdEntry {
    pub fd:     u64,
    pub inode:  u64,
    pub flags:  i32,
    pub uid:    u32,
    pub gid:    u32,
    pub offset: u64,
}
```

`flags` and `inode` are logically immutable after construction; `offset` is mutable for future use. We don't enforce this with field visibility — the library crate is the only consumer and we trust internal call sites.

---

## `pub struct FdTable`
<!-- checksum: rust-fdtable-3 -->

### Purpose
Owns the live fds for one `Filesystem`. Provides minting, lookup, close, and per-inode open-count queries.

### Invariants
- `next_fd` is a monotonic counter starting at 1 (fd 0 is reserved, as a Rust-idiomatic spare).
- `next_fd` never decreases.
- No two entries share the same fd.
- Closing an fd removes it from `entries` and does NOT recycle its number.

### Postconditions
- `FdTable::new()` returns a fresh, empty table with `next_fd = 1`.
- `open(inode, flags, uid, gid)` returns a fresh fd and inserts the entry.
- `get(fd)` returns a reference to the entry or `Err(Error::BadFileDescriptor)`.
- `close(fd)` removes the entry and returns the inode it pointed at, or `Err(Error::BadFileDescriptor)` if unknown.
- `open_count(inode)` returns the number of live fds for that inode.
- `fds_for_inode(inode)` returns the fd numbers.

### Implementation Notes

```rust
pub struct FdTable {
    entries: HashMap<u64, FdEntry>,
    next_fd: u64,
}

impl FdTable {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self { entries: HashMap::new(), next_fd: 1 }
    }

    pub fn open(&mut self, inode: u64, flags: i32, uid: u32, gid: u32) -> u64 {
        let fd = self.next_fd;
        self.next_fd += 1;
        self.entries.insert(fd, FdEntry { fd, inode, flags, uid, gid, offset: 0 });
        fd
    }

    pub fn get(&self, fd: u64) -> Result<&FdEntry> {
        self.entries.get(&fd)
            .ok_or_else(|| Error::BadFileDescriptor(format!("unknown fd {fd}")))
    }

    pub fn get_mut(&mut self, fd: u64) -> Result<&mut FdEntry> {
        self.entries.get_mut(&fd)
            .ok_or_else(|| Error::BadFileDescriptor(format!("unknown fd {fd}")))
    }

    pub fn close(&mut self, fd: u64) -> Result<u64> {
        self.entries.remove(&fd)
            .map(|e| e.inode)
            .ok_or_else(|| Error::BadFileDescriptor(format!("unknown fd {fd}")))
    }

    pub fn open_count(&self, inode: u64) -> usize {
        self.entries.values().filter(|e| e.inode == inode).count()
    }

    pub fn fds_for_inode(&self, inode: u64) -> Vec<u64> {
        self.entries.values().filter(|e| e.inode == inode).map(|e| e.fd).collect()
    }
}

impl Default for FdTable {
    fn default() -> Self { Self::new() }
}
```

### Failure Modes
- `get` / `get_mut` / `close` on an unknown fd: `Err(Error::BadFileDescriptor)`. **propagated**.

